---
import PipeBlock from "../PipeBlock.astro";
---

<section class="motivation wrap">
  <h2>Why a language.</h2>
  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <p>
        Configuration files describe state. Pipelines describe motion.
        Luna Pipes treats agent skills as <em>words</em> and composition as
        <em>grammar</em>: a tradition older than JSON, sharper than YAML,
        and built for the way work actually runs.
      </p>
      <p>
        Forth, Joy, Factor, and Unix proved you can build a programming
        language from one good idea: concatenation. <code>f g h</code>
        means do <code>f</code>, then <code>g</code>, then <code>h</code>,
        passing the value along. Luna Pipes adapts this for the agent era.
        The unit of composition is not a function call; it is a skill
        invocation. The runtime is your machine.
      </p>
    </div>
    <aside class="margin-note">
      <p>
        <small>
          Prior art: McIlroy's pipe at Bell Labs, 1973. Moore's Forth, 1970.
          von Thun's Joy, 2001. Pestov's Factor, 2003. All concatenative,
          all functional in spirit, all underused.
        </small>
      </p>
    </aside>
  </div>

  <PipeBlock
    caption="The same expression, three ways."
    code={'/persona generate >> ghost "post" >> publish notion'}
    output={['composed: 3 stages, sequential']}
  />
  <PipeBlock
    caption="With repetition."
    code={'/persona generate >> ghost "post" *4 >> publish notion'}
    output={['composed: 6 stages, ghost runs 4 times in parallel, then publish']}
  />
  <PipeBlock
    caption="With branching."
    code={'/persona generate >> ? premium >> ghost "longform" : ghost "short"'}
    output={['composed: branches on the truthy `premium` flag']}
  />
</section>

<style>
  .motivation { padding-top: var(--t-6); padding-bottom: var(--t-12); }
  .two-col {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, var(--measure)) minmax(0, 22ch);
    gap: var(--t-6);
    align-items: start;
    margin-bottom: var(--t-6);
  }
  .margin-note {
    border-left: 1px solid var(--rule);
    padding-left: var(--t-3);
    margin-top: var(--t-2);
  }
  .margin-note p { margin: 0; }
  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .two-col { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .margin-note { border-left: 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); padding-left: 0; padding-top: var(--t-2); }
  }
</style>
